            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Amer Hadzic\u2019s first memories are not of a place, but of a feeling: the hurried grip of his mother's hand and the low hum of fear. Born in Sarajevo in 1989, his early childhood was erased by the Bosnian War. His family fled as refugees, eventually settling in a small, tight-knit Bosnian community in St. Louis. Growing up, Amer straddled two worlds: the stoic, traumatized world of his parents, who worked tirelessly at cleaning jobs, and the alien landscape of American high school. He felt permanently out of sync, and his academic performance suffered. He scraped by, earning a GED, the weight of his unspoken history a constant, heavy companion.\n\nHis early twenties were marked by anger and a sense of displacement. A series of dead-end jobs left him feeling hollow until a court-mandated counseling session, stemming from a minor public disturbance, became an unexpected turning point. The counselor, a veteran, recognized the deep-seated trauma beneath Amer\u2019s rebellious exterior. For the first time, Amer felt seen. This experience ignited a profound desire to do for others what that counselor had done for him. He pursued certification as a Peer Support Specialist, realizing his greatest wound could be his most powerful tool.\n\nDrawn to its robust social services and diverse communities, Amer moved to San Francisco seven years ago. He found a job at a non-profit in Hayes Valley that assists refugee and immigrant youth. His modest apartment in the Inner Richmond is his sanctuary. His daily 3.5-mile bicycle commute is a non-negotiable ritual, a time to process the emotionally taxing stories he hears at work.\n\nAmer\u2019s social circle is small but deep, comprised of a few fellow Balkan immigrants and colleagues who understand the demands of their work. He keeps in close contact with his parents, their bond forged in survival. His dream is simple: to save enough to one day visit Sarajevo, not as a fleeing child, but as a man who understands his own story. For Amer, San Francisco isn't a final destination but a proving ground, a city where he uses the fragments of his broken past to help others piece together their own futures."
