            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe sat stiffly in the chair, ready for a lecture. But the counselor, a man with weary eyes who mentioned his own time in the service, didn't lecture. He just listened to Amer\u2019s rage. After a long silence, he said, \"Sounds like you\u2019ve been carrying a war inside you for a long time.\" The words cracked something open. For the first time, Amer didn't feel judged, but understood. The anger didn't vanish, but it finally had a name. That moment, in a sterile St. Louis office twelve years ago, was his true beginning.\n\n2.\nHe remembers his first week in San Francisco, taking the N-Judah all the way to Ocean Beach. He\u2019d expected the Golden Gate Bridge to move him, but it was this\u2014the vast, roaring expanse of the Pacific. As a child, water meant crossing a river in darkness, a border to escape. Here, the ocean wasn't an obstacle, but an endless horizon. Standing on the cold sand seven years ago, the scale of it didn't make him feel small; it made him feel that a new story was finally possible.\n\n3.\nFour years ago, he was at his friend Sasha\u2019s apartment in the Mission. They were drinking thick Bosnian coffee and eating burek Sasha's mother had sent. For a few hours, the familiar cadence of their language filled the small kitchen, drowning out the city noise. No one had to explain the sadness behind a joke or the history in a sigh. Looking at his friends, Amer realized home wasn't just a place he'd fled. It was a feeling he could build, even here, thousands of miles away, one cup of coffee at a time.\n\n4.\nHe remembers a ride home two years ago, after a young Afghan boy described his family\u2019s escape. Pushing his bike up an incline on JFK Drive, the wind biting his face, he focused on the burn in his thighs, the rhythm of his breathing. With each pedal stroke, he pushed the boy's inherited trauma, and his own, out through his feet. By the time he saw the fog creeping over the Presidio, he felt lighter\u2014not empty, but cleansed. The ride had become more than a commute; it was his therapy.\n\n5.\nThere was a Somali girl at the center last year who hadn't spoken for weeks. He found her staring out a window in Hayes Valley. He didn't ask questions. He just sat nearby and said, \"Sometimes, the quiet is the loudest place, you know?\" She looked at him, a flicker of recognition in her eyes, and finally whispered about the boat. In that shared silence that followed, Amer felt the jagged pieces of his own past click into place. He wasn't just healing himself; he was becoming a place of healing."
